you know, trigger points for self-harm or where you have to think about putting in safety

239
00:15:07,966 --> 00:15:11,169
nets and contact points for people who might be having suicidal thoughts.

240
00:15:11,989 --> 00:15:16,533
And you very, I mean, these are very sobering conversations, very, very fast that you don't

241
00:15:16,573 --> 00:15:17,133
necessarily have.

242
00:15:17,514 --> 00:15:23,118
There's also a whole bunch of legal issues here about questions of...

243
00:15:26,993 --> 00:15:36,323
libel I guess in terms of suggesting if there was kind of a any direct negligence that led up to

244
00:15:36,383 --> 00:15:41,568
Joyce's death and the failure to discover her body. You know because these are all this only

245
00:15:41,608 --> 00:15:44,811
happened a few years ago all the people involved in the story are still alive we're going to play

246
00:15:44,851 --> 00:15:45,272
this thing.

247
00:15:47,088 --> 00:15:53,374
And so you're very quickly aware that you're navigating in this kind of very complicated space.

248
00:15:53,394 --> 00:15:54,995
And we got a lot of help from Film 4 in doing that.

249
00:15:55,035 --> 00:15:58,438
We spent a lot of time talking to people like Missing People,

250
00:15:58,498 --> 00:16:04,023
which is the big missing persons charity in the UK, to try and kind of get our heads around all of these issues.

251
00:16:05,264 --> 00:16:12,551
Because the problem with a project like this is it's not just about keeping the lawyers happy.

252
00:16:14,035 --> 00:16:16,397
It's really a lot about not being an asshole.

253
00:16:18,078 --> 00:16:20,140
Because you hear the story, and everybody has their own

254
00:16:20,160 --> 00:16:21,021
immediate reaction to it.

255
00:16:21,061 --> 00:16:22,902
And I think quite a lot of people had a reaction.

256
00:16:23,002 --> 00:16:26,305
I certainly had a reaction, where you go, oh, god, I

257
00:16:26,325 --> 00:16:27,025
should ring my brother.

258
00:16:27,085 --> 00:16:29,527
I've not spoken to my brother in like three months.

259
00:16:29,567 --> 00:16:30,708
That's inexcusable.

260
00:16:30,768 --> 00:16:31,369
I should fix that.

261
00:16:31,409 --> 00:16:31,849
I should do that.

262
00:16:31,889 --> 00:16:32,629
I should call my granny.

263
00:16:32,650 --> 00:16:33,290
I should do this thing.

264
00:16:33,330 --> 00:16:35,952
I should bang on my neighbor's door and introduce myself,

265
00:16:35,972 --> 00:16:37,013
because I still don't know their names,

266
00:16:37,053 --> 00:16:37,613
or whatever it is.

267
00:16:39,230 --> 00:16:42,873
you very quickly start having ideas about how you might

268
00:16:42,933 --> 00:16:45,855
structure a game experience that revolves around doing those

269
00:16:45,915 --> 00:16:46,376
kind of things.

270
00:16:48,137 --> 00:16:51,059
And possibly, revolves around doing those kind of things in

271
00:16:51,099 --> 00:16:51,980
machine-readable ways.

272
00:16:52,040 --> 00:16:54,042
So you start to have over-excited ideas about

273
00:16:54,642 --> 00:16:57,665
scraping people's Facebook accounts for a whole bunch of

274
00:16:57,705 --> 00:17:01,208
information about the size and richness of

275
00:17:01,248 --> 00:17:02,068
their friendship group.

276
00:17:03,249 --> 00:17:05,229
and looking at how often they contact people

277
00:17:05,349 --> 00:17:07,250
and prompting them to get in touch with people

278
00:17:07,270 --> 00:17:08,790
that they haven't contacted for a while

279
00:17:08,830 --> 00:17:09,530
and all this kind of thing.

280
00:17:10,250 --> 00:17:13,431
And then you realize that you have no business doing that.

281
00:17:13,471 --> 00:17:16,112
You have no idea who these people are.

282
00:17:16,652 --> 00:17:18,712
The machine-readable portions of their social lives

283
00:17:18,752 --> 00:17:20,053
are only ever portions.

284
00:17:21,133 --> 00:17:24,714
None of you have lives that are fully and wholly represented

285
00:17:25,154 --> 00:17:26,634
in Facebook or on Twitter or whatever it is

286
00:17:26,674 --> 00:17:28,414
that you tend to be.

287
00:17:28,975 --> 00:17:29,895
There's people who are there,

288
00:17:29,915 --> 00:17:30,755
there's people who are not there,

289
00:17:30,815 --> 00:17:31,995
there's maybe people who.

290
00:17:33,836 --> 00:17:37,559
are there who it looks like you never interact with but that's because you see them every day

291
00:17:37,679 --> 00:17:41,681
or you IM them every day or you know whatever else is going on and trying to reconstruct.

292
00:17:43,627 --> 00:17:46,870
a true reflection of somebody's degree of connectedness

293
00:17:47,651 --> 00:17:49,834
from digitally scrapable sources.

294
00:17:50,955 --> 00:17:53,718
Again, the minute you poke at it for more than two seconds

295
00:17:53,838 --> 00:17:55,180
is clearly not a good idea.

296
00:17:56,041 --> 00:17:57,903
Even if you remove the machine readable portion

297
00:17:58,203 --> 00:18:01,948
and just say, how long is it since you called your mother?

298
00:18:02,868 --> 00:18:05,589
you may have a really good reason for not having called your mother.

299
00:18:06,149 --> 00:18:09,410
I have no business, my game has no business telling you that you ought to do that.

300
00:18:10,110 --> 00:18:12,691
And what you find is you, you...

301
00:18:13,131 --> 00:18:15,012
So you step away from that specificity,

302
00:18:16,492 --> 00:18:19,693
and you try and find something that is gentler and more open to interpretation,

303
00:18:19,733 --> 00:18:22,373
and then you end up with something that is so wishy-washy and so vague

304
00:18:22,894 --> 00:18:24,134
that nobody cares.

305
00:18:24,154 --> 00:18:29,455
It's like, hey, maybe you should think about a thing that you don't think about if you'd like.

306
00:18:30,829 --> 00:18:33,096
It's not like, you know, that's not hooky.

307
00:18:33,237 --> 00:18:35,605
That's not kind of what you want.

308
00:18:35,625 --> 00:18:35,806
So that.

309
00:18:37,838 --> 00:18:42,759
you know, that became really important to us. I think particularly when we talk to people like the Missing People charity,

310
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:48,901
you start to realize lots of things that I hadn't perhaps thought about before as much as I should, that, you know,

311
00:18:48,921 --> 00:18:53,323
sometimes people go missing because they want to go missing. Sometimes people are isolated because they enjoy solitude.

312
00:18:53,343 --> 00:19:00,705
They're happy working that way. Sometimes people like mediating nearly all of their friendships and social life digitally.

313
00:19:00,725 --> 00:19:05,367
And that doesn't mean there's anything deficient in that. It doesn't mean there's anything deficient if you don't want to do anything.

314
00:19:05,507 --> 00:19:09,871
digitally and you want to do everything down the pub in real life. It was very difficult

315
00:19:09,931 --> 00:19:15,256
to find any firm ground of a thing that we felt we could say that didn't involve being

316
00:19:15,276 --> 00:19:24,965
an asshole. And that led into another realization that really affected the development direction

317
00:19:25,005 --> 00:19:26,366
of the project.

318
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:35,421
One of the saddest things at the heart of Joyce's story is she was found by accident.

319
00:19:35,601 --> 00:19:36,622
No one knew she was there.

320
00:19:36,682 --> 00:19:37,582
No one was looking.

321
00:19:38,462 --> 00:19:44,024
Her neighbor had become a bit frustrated the previous year at the noise from the television

322
00:19:44,124 --> 00:19:47,085
and had banged on the wall a bit, but when it hadn't worked, he'd given up.

323
00:19:49,926 --> 00:19:54,727
And that felt incredibly important to me, that this reality, that...

324
00:19:55,997 --> 00:19:59,358
this terrible thing had happened and we just didn't know and nobody did anything and nobody

325
00:19:59,398 --> 00:20:03,000
was looking and there was no sense of quest, there was no sense of mission, it was a really

326
00:20:03,080 --> 00:20:07,441
interesting thing to take into a game design context because so often that's our structure.

327
00:20:07,582 --> 00:20:10,703
I mean arguably it's always our structure, but there's a thing you're trying to do, there's

328
00:20:10,723 --> 00:20:14,805
a point you're trying to get to, there's a, you know, there's some kind of mission statement

329
00:20:14,865 --> 00:20:16,145
or a goal objective.

330
00:20:17,366 --> 00:20:19,266
And you know.

331
00:20:21,507 --> 00:20:23,609
Obviously we didn't want to do crass ways to do that.

332
00:20:23,669 --> 00:20:26,891
We would, I don't think we would have felt at all comfortable kind of making a game where

333
00:20:26,931 --> 00:20:33,014
your job was to save Joyce or, you know, find her earlier or, you know, whatever that could

334
00:20:33,034 --> 00:20:33,354
have been.

335
00:20:33,715 --> 00:20:37,557
But even if you make it oblique, it just started to feel, um...

336
00:20:39,827 --> 00:20:43,270
totally and thematically wrong. Putting you in a structure that was about going,

337
00:20:43,310 --> 00:20:47,012
hey, you know, your job is to do this stuff and that will work,

338
00:20:47,833 --> 00:20:51,215
just felt to be a structure that was everything that the film and Joyce's

339
00:20:51,235 --> 00:20:55,558
story wasn't about. And it was probably about this point

340
00:20:55,578 --> 00:20:59,601
that we started to get quite scared, because it's like, okay, so now

341
00:20:59,741 --> 00:21:01,963
we can't even kind of have that structure.

342
00:21:02,583 --> 00:21:06,546
So we're not going to use Joyce's narrative, we're not going to use...

343
00:21:07,688 --> 00:21:10,770
that kind of conventional game mission structure.

344
00:21:11,530 --> 00:21:14,572
And then the difficulty is, even when

345
00:21:14,612 --> 00:21:17,754
you start looking on a systemic level, it's really difficult.

346
00:21:17,974 --> 00:21:22,277
So a lot of, and certainly a lot of the work

347
00:21:22,317 --> 00:21:25,839
we've done in gamifying with no air quotes things,

348
00:21:26,380 --> 00:21:28,541
and a lot of what the other people have done,

349
00:21:28,801 --> 00:21:31,143
is looking for those essential systems,

350
00:21:31,203 --> 00:21:34,525
is looking at how you boil something down to something

351
00:21:35,760 --> 00:21:40,982
revelatory and interesting about the kind of interplay of key elements within that system.

352
00:21:41,962 --> 00:21:45,703
That's great because games thrive on those structures.

353
00:21:47,384 --> 00:21:54,786
But I think this is interesting because we've talked here often enough about whether or not

354
00:21:54,846 --> 00:22:00,268
it's a realistic goal that we'll ever be able to model the muddier elements of the human

355
00:22:00,288 --> 00:22:02,728
condition in that kind of a way. And

356
00:22:04,892 --> 00:22:10,298
Joyce's story just seemed like, you know, this incredible object lesson in how functionally impossible that is.

357
00:22:10,919 --> 00:22:16,926
The systems, there are systems that sit under Joyce's story.

358
00:22:18,047 --> 00:22:20,690
All kinds of systems. There's administrative and institutional systems.

359
00:22:20,730 --> 00:22:21,311
It was clear that...

360
00:22:22,122 --> 00:22:28,088
it became clear from Carol's research that there was some history of domestic violence

361
00:22:28,108 --> 00:22:33,232
there and that had put her into a system which had provided her with safe housing but had

362
00:22:33,312 --> 00:22:36,895
probably broken her connections with the places that she'd been living prior to that happening.

