00:25:42,231 --> 00:25:46,433
and graphical text adventure design, and thinking about, oh,

412
00:25:46,453 --> 00:25:47,913
we were so pleased when we came up with this,

413
00:25:48,313 --> 00:25:51,754
thinking about if we could create this environment that

414
00:25:51,774 --> 00:25:53,435
may or may not be graphically represented,

415
00:25:53,495 --> 00:25:55,355
that you navigate it in the way that you navigate a text

416
00:25:55,395 --> 00:25:56,356
adventure, broadly speaking.

417
00:25:56,376 --> 00:25:58,776
So you're moving through a sequence of rooms or spaces.

418
00:26:01,277 --> 00:26:02,657
And that would present you with.

419
00:26:05,895 --> 00:26:10,279
Versions of the kinds of puzzles and challenges that you're maybe familiar with from text

420
00:26:10,319 --> 00:26:14,862
adventures. So there are locked doors, there are characters perhaps you won't let you pass,

421
00:26:14,882 --> 00:26:21,988
there are things to navigate. But rather than giving you the kind of tools that often those

422
00:26:22,028 --> 00:26:26,731
games give you of, you know, candles and bits of rope and keys and all the rest of it, we

423
00:26:26,751 --> 00:26:28,292
would ask you to draw those from your own life.

424
00:26:28,953 --> 00:26:35,800
So there would be a room where to move on from that room you would need to leave something behind that was, you know, an object that was precious to you.

425
00:26:36,100 --> 00:26:49,014
Or a door, probably wouldn't be a door that would only open if you would tell it the name of someone you never told you loved and you wished you had, or whatever it was, maybe a bit less terribly mawkish than that.

426
00:26:49,975 --> 00:26:59,157
And then the process of puzzle solving would be the process of reuniting and restructuring those things and hopefully finding some interesting perspectives on, you know, on how those things work together.

427
00:26:59,217 --> 00:27:09,240
So you would move through this space and, you know, in the end, make progress not by unlocking the blue key with the blue door, but in the end, by, you know, giving your.

428
00:27:10,622 --> 00:27:14,863
grandmother's engagement ring to your high school crush or whatever unresolved thing

429
00:27:15,003 --> 00:27:17,464
we had uncovered in the course of doing that.

430
00:27:18,044 --> 00:27:21,966
And we thought that this whole thing might play out, the big reveal at the end would

431
00:27:22,006 --> 00:27:27,728
be that in the choices that you'd made in navigating this space, you were actually navigating

432
00:27:27,788 --> 00:27:32,730
on this map that told you something about yourself in terms of where you situated yourself

433
00:27:33,170 --> 00:27:35,891
on that grid in terms of whether you were somebody who...

434
00:27:37,850 --> 00:27:43,477
gravitated to crowds or liked to solitude or was somebody who was kind of more digitally or

435
00:27:43,497 --> 00:27:48,903
physically native and then that might be a thing that we could kind of map and take out to the

436
00:27:49,243 --> 00:27:51,786
world as a whole as kind of something that had arisen from this game.

437
00:27:53,120 --> 00:27:54,922
There's a lot about that idea not to like.

